<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">35081759</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2022</Year><Month>04</Month><Day>18</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2024</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>27</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">2168-6602</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>36</Volume><Issue>4</Issue><PubDate><Year>2022</Year><Month>May</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>American journal of health promotion : AJHP</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Am J Health Promot</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Smoke-free Ordinances and Youth Tobacco Use in Kentucky.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>673</StartPage><EndPage>677</EndPage><MedlinePgn>673-677</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1177/08901171211066913</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE">Determine associations of strength of local smoke-free laws and urban/rural location with cigarette and smokeless tobacco use among high school students in grades 10 and 12.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="DESIGN">Secondary data analysis from the 2004-2018 biennial Kentucky Incentives for Prevention Survey.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="SETTING">Public high schools in Kentucky.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="SAMPLE">N = 353502 10<sup>th</sup>/12<sup>th</sup> graders.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="MEASURES">County-level smoke-free law status from the Kentucky Center for Smoke-free Policy; Rural Urban Continuum Codes; self-reported last 30-day alcohol, marijuana, cigarette, and smokeless tobacco use.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="ANALYSIS">Generalized estimating equations modeling assessed the association of law status and urban/rural location with tobacco use across cohorts, controlling for demographics and other substance use.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS">Students in counties with a comprehensive smoke-free law were 23% less likely to smoke cigarettes and 16% less likely to use smokeless, compared to those in counties without a law. Students in counties with moderate/weak laws did not differ in likelihood of use for either product, compared to those in counties without a law. Students in urban counties were 14% less likely to smoke, but there was no difference in likelihood of smokeless use by urban/rural location.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION">Comprehensive smoke-free laws are associated with a lower likelihood of youth cigarette and smokeless use. Rural youth may be at increased risk of cigarette smoking relative to youth in urban areas.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Rayens</LastName><ForeName>Mary Kay</ForeName><Initials>MK</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0001-8465-8763</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>University of Kentucky Colleges of Nursing and Public Health, Lexington, KY, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>McGeeney</LastName><ForeName>Teresa</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>REACH Evaluation, Louisville, KY, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wiggins</LastName><ForeName>Amanda T</ForeName><Initials>AT</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Ringgold ID: 4530University of Kentucky College of Nursing, Lexington, KY, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Bucher</LastName><ForeName>Amanda</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Ringgold ID: 4530University of Kentucky College of Nursing, Lexington, KY, USA.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Ickes</LastName><ForeName>Melinda</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0003-3198-2812</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Ringgold ID: 5170University of Kentucky College of Education, Lexington, KY, USA.</Affiliation>